{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488351"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:38:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:38:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"419"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/419"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.07,0.07,0.05,0.78]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"419"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76736"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/419"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"419"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62229"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"112"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"2066"},{"type":"tags","id":"2116"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"304"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12392"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44618"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76736","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76736"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine urological assessment. He does not have any symptoms of bladder neck outflow obstruction. He has a medical history of myocardial infarction and stent insertion 18 months ago. His medications include aspirin and clopidogrel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The prostate feels normal on digital rectal examination. His prostate-specific antigen (PSA) is 3.9 ng/mL (0-4). Two years earlier he had a PSA level of 2.3 ng/mL. An ultrasound examination shows the prostate to be of normal size and appearances. Of 12 ultrasound-guided biopsies, one shows a 3 mm focus of Gleason 3+3=6 (Grade Group 1). A multiparametric MRI of the prostate reveals a 5 mm lesion with a PI-RADS score of 2.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management option?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Brachytherapy","External beam radiotherapy","Radical prostatectomy","Transurethral prostatectomy","Active surveillance"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has low-risk prostate cancer based on his Gleason score of 3+3=6 (Grade Group 1), PSA level, and multiparametric MRI findings. The Gleason score indicates that this tumour is low-grade or well-differentiated, and the patient is likely to do well and less likely to progress to advanced prostatic cancer than those with a higher score. The PI-RADS score of 2 on multiparametric MRI also suggests a low likelihood of clinically significant cancer. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProstate Imaging Reporting and Data System (PI-RADS) is used by radiologists to report the likelihood that a suspicious area is a clinically significant cancer. The PI-RADS score ranges from 1 (most likely not cancer) to 5 (very suspicious):\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERADS 1\u2014Very low (clinically significant cancer is highly unlikely to be present)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPI-RADS 2\u2014Low (clinically significant cancer is unlikely to be present)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPI-RADS 3\u2014Intermediate (the presence of clinically significant cancer is equivocal)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPI-RADS 4\u2014High (clinically significant cancer is likely to be present)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPI-RADS 5\u2014Very high (clinically significant cancer is highly likely to be present)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven these factors and the patient\u0027s co-morbidities, \u003Cstrong\u003Eactive surveillance\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management option.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadical prostatectomy\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eexternal beam radiotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E are more aggressive treatments typically reserved for higher-risk prostate cancers or when active surveillance shows disease progression. These options carry higher risks of complications, including urinary incontinence and erectile dysfunction, which may significantly impact quality of life.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBrachytherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is another form of radiation therapy that involves placing radioactive seeds directly into the prostate. While it can be an option for some low-risk prostate cancers, it is generally not the first-line approach for patients who are good candidates for active surveillance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransurethral prostatectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used to treat benign prostatic hyperplasia and is not an appropriate treatment for prostate cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA report in the New England Journal of Medicine showed that while patients undergoing active surveillance had slightly higher rates of metastatic disease compared with those who had either radical prostatectomy or radiotherapy, the ten-year survival of all three groups was similar. In terms of quality of life (urinary and sexual function), the conservatively managed group had better outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Active surveillance is recommended for asymptomatic patients with a low Gleason score and low-risk features on multiparametric MRI.","Multiparametric MRI with PI-RADS scoring is an important tool in the assessment and management of prostate cancer."],"references":["Hamdy FC, Donovan JL, Lane JA, Mason M, Metcalfe C, Holding P, et al. 10-Year Outcomes after Monitoring, Surgery, or Radiotherapy for Localized Prostate Cancer. N Engl J Med. 2016;375:1415-24. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27626136/","Briganti A, Fossati N, Catto JWF, Cornford P, Montorsi F, Mottet N, Wirth M, Van Poppel H. Active Surveillance for Low-risk Prostate Cancer: The European Association of Urology Position in 2018. Eur Urol. 2018 Sep;74(3):357-368. doi: 10.1016/j.eururo.2018.06.008. Epub 2018 Jun 22. PMID: 29937198.","Ho MD, Ross AE, Eggener SE. Risk Stratification of Low-risk Prostate Cancer: Individualizing Care in the Era of Active Surveillance. J Urol. 2023 Jul;210(1):38-45. doi: 10.1097/JU.0000000000003454. Epub 2023 Apr 12. PMID: 37042807."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62229"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"419"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62229","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62229"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-04T19:39:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-04T19:39:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"419"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76736"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{